<subsection><title> Summary </title>

 	<p>
        This chapter introduced the foundational concepts of differential equations (DEs). Below are the key terms and ideas covered. Clicking on <c>A4</c> or <c>US</c>, will give you a printer-friendly version of this summary if you would like to print it as a reference for your studies.
    </p>

	<worksheet  ><title>Chapter Terms and Key Ideas</title>

		<p>
		<assemblage color="green">
			<p>
				<dl>
					<li xml:id="summary-de"><title> Differential Equation  (DE) </title>
						<p>
							An equation that involves one or more derivatives of an unknown function. 
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-dependent-variable"><title> Dependent Variable </title>
						<p>
							The variable representing the unknown function in a DE. It is always the variable to which derivatives are applied.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-independent-variable"><title> Independent Variable </title>
						<p>
							The variable which the dependent variable changes with respect to.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-terms"><title> Terms </title>
						<p>
							The expressions in a DE separated by <m>+</m>, <m>-</m>, or <m>=</m>.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-coefficients"><title> Coefficients </title>
						<p>
							The part of a term multiplied by the dependent variable or its derivatives.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-constant-term"><title> Constant Term </title>
						<p>
							A term in a DE that does not contain the dependent variable or its derivatives.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-order"><title> Order </title>
						<p>
							The highest derivative present in a DE.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-linear-term"><title> Linear Term </title>
						<p>
							A term of the form:
						</p>
						<p>
							<me>a(t)\ y,\ a(t)\ y',\ a(t)\ y'',\ a(t)\ y''',\ \ldots</me>,
						</p>
						<p>
							where <m>y</m> is the dependent variable, and <m>a(t)</m> is a coefficient that depends only on the independent variable <m>t</m>.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-linear"><title> Linear DE </title>
						<p>
							A DE composed entirely of linear terms.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-nonlinear"><title> Nonlinear DE </title>
						<p>
							A DE that contains at least one nonlinear term.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-satisfies"><title> Satisfying a DE </title>
						<p>
							A function satisfies a DE if substituting it for the dependent variable reduces the equation to a true statement, such as <m>0 = 0</m>.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-solution"><title> Solution </title>
						<p>
							A function that satisfies the DE.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-general-solution"><title> General Solution </title>
						<p>
							The common form (template) of all the solutions in the family. It contains constants that can take any value.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-particular-solution"><title> Particular Solution </title>
						<p>
							A single solution obtained by assigning specific values to the constants in the general solution.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-family-of-solutions"><title> Family of Solutions </title>
						<p>
							The collection of all possible particular solutions.
						</p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="summary-initial-conditions"><title> Initial Conditions </title>
						<p>
							Known values of the solution or its derivatives at a specific point, used to determine a unique particular solution from the general solution.
						</p>
					</li>
				</dl>
			</p>
		</assemblage>
		</p>
	</worksheet>

    <p>
        This summary serves as a reference for the key concepts and terminology introduced in this chapter. As you move forward, these foundational ideas will be essential for understanding and solving differential equations in greater depth.
    </p>

